    <div id="integrity" class="jumbotron">
        <h2>2. Integrity & Openness - Embrace Integrity and Openness</h2>
        <p align="right" style="font-size:10px"><a href="#top" style="color:black">Back to Top</a></p>
        <b>Intention</b>
        <ul align="left">
            <li>We set and live by the highest ethical standards in all our dealings whether it is internal or external. </li>
            <li>We value strong, positive relationships that are open and honest.  This is a big part of what differentiates Centric and allows us to accomplish much more than we would be able to otherwise.</li>
            <li>We always act with integrity in our relationships, and demonstrate compassion, loyalty, and honesty.</li>
        </ul>


        <h3>Visioning</h3>
        <p>
            <button data-toggle="collapse" data-target="#demo2">Read the story behind integrity and openness</button>

            <div id="demo2" class="collapse">
                Adriana and Jonathan from the Miami business unit developed a relationship with Get-Away Cruise Lines which quickly led to an opportunity to build a custom SharePoint solution.  The fact that there were not any employees in Miami with SharePoint experience was not an obstacle to accepting this challenging project.
                The Atlanta Solution Center quickly stepped in and provided knowledgeable resources to help craft a winning proposal response and a team of talented individuals who could develop the solution remotely.  The Miami office provided all of the other resources required to successfully manage and execute the project, including Business Analysts, Quality Assurance and integration specialists.
                Unfortunately, midway through the engagement, the client requested a series of changes to the original specification.  This would change the original design and create some re-work for the development team that had already begun building the solution.  José, the Project Lead, knew that an honest conversation with the client sponsors was needed because of the impact to the timeline and the team if they moved ahead with the requested changes.  He was not willing to over-commit his team for the sake of client satisfaction given the risk of burnout and poor delivery results from working too many hours.
                The Delivery Excellence team assigned to the engagement, Noah and Olivia, met with the client sponsors and José to work through the dilemma.  They used the Crucial Conversation techniques that all Centric employees integrate into their consulting tool box to create an open, honest dialogue to determine the best course of action to meet their needs.  They were able to establish a new direction and timeline that allowed the team to successfully deliver the additional features that Get-Away Cruise Lines desired, while maintaining work-life balance for the team.
                A few weeks later, the schedule showed signs of slipping.  Frank, a developer from another consulting firm who was a member of the project team, began regularly missing deadlines.  José was once again challenged to address this situation which threatened to derail the entire project schedule if it continued.  Frank always had a legitimate reason for missing his deadlines, so the first and second occurrences were overlooked when he promised not to let it happen again.  When it happened again, José decided he needed to sit down with Frank and have a dialogue.
                Jose started by admitting to Frank that he had not adequately focused on the due dates for assigned work on the project and had been distracted by other tasks on his list.  He committed to doing a daily 15 minute stand up each morning to review progress and identify issues being encountered for each team member.  Frank immediately relaxed as he had been worrying about his missed deadlines.  He candidly talked to José about the difficulty he was having with a particular feature he was coding and admitted he was trying to squeeze out some additional time to work out the bug.
                José talked to him about how they could approach the problem so that Frank had the support that he needed and collectively decided to pull in a Senior Developer on the team to review the code and assist.  By the next afternoon, the issue was resolved and all of the tasks were back on schedule.  The sense of collaboration and trust was increased on the team and José was reminded that it is better to have a difficult conversation and head off problems before they have a chance to take root.Together, the team members from Miami and the Atlanta Solution Center far exceeded the CIO’s expectations at Get-Away Cruise Lines on the project delivery and established a foundation of trust through the ongoing open dialogue.   Get-Away became an anchor account for Miami bringing in approximately 10% of the annual revenue target for the business unit.  Another challenge that had surfaced early in the engagement was that the typical project delivery model was not working well in this environment.  The team brainstormed options and implemented  a creative customized approach utilizing Centric’s internal SharePoint project collaboration site that enabled Get-Away Cruise Lines SMEs to view and edit business requirements quickly vastly expediting the requirements gathering process while at the same time improving the quality of the requirements.
                In the process of working through a new model that seamlessly integrated the Solution Center team, the relationships established brought employees together in a collaborative, positive way.  Not only were the work products high quality, but all of the team members loved coming to work every day and finding ways to contribute and collaborate.
                The team walked away with a greater appreciation for the benefits of trust, honesty and transparency in how they deal with each other and their clients which is what helps keeps Centric strong and differentiates Centric from most of the competition!
            </div>
           
        </p>
